                  , on the <rs id="t18290910-310-cd1710" type="crimeDate">15th of August</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290910-310-off1709 t18290910-310-cd1710"></join>, at St. George, and stealing therein, 2 frocks, value 2s.; 1 bed-gown, value 6s.; 1 pelisse, value 4s.; 9 yards of printed cotton, value 7s.; 1 scarf, value 3s., and 1 shawl, value 5s., her property
            </rs>.</p>

               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-310-person2904">
                  REBECCA 
                  SMITH
               <interp inst="t18290910-310-person2904" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-310-person2904" type="given" value="REBECCA"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-310-person2904" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18290910-310-viclabel1711" type="occupation">widow</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290910-310-victim2903 t18290910-310-viclabel1711"></join>, and have three children - I live at No. 2, <placeName id="t18290910-310-crimeloc1712">Church-lane, in the parish of St. George</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290910-310-crimeloc1712" type="placeName" value="Church-lane, in the parish of St. George"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290910-310-crimeloc1712" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290910-310-off1709 t18290910-310-crimeloc1712"></join>. On Saturday. the 15th of August, I went out at half-past eleven o'clock in the morning - there are no lodgers; it is a small house, with two rooms and a kitchen; I locked my door, and saw two bad boys throwing stones; I turned back, and put my shutters too - my children were at that time at school, and no one was in the house; I locked my door very particularly, and when I came home at a quarter-past twelve o'clock, I met my little boy, who had come home from school; he said to me,"How came you to leave your window open;" I went to the house, and found the window was open, and the curtain torn down; the parlour door was wide open - my drawers were open, and the property stated was gone; the person had got in by pulling open the shutters, and lifting up the window, which was down, and fastened by a latch. I found my property at a pawnbroker's on the Monday - I know the prisoner, and knew his father; they did live three or four doors from my house, but they had moved a short time before; his father is a watchman.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-310-person2905">
                  JOHN 
